## Output Path — FOUR FILES PER OBJECT

> **⛔ CRITICAL: The `.md` file IS the wiki. The `.review-needed.md` is a lightweight sidecar. These are DIFFERENT files with DIFFERENT purposes. Writing wiki content into `.review-needed.md` and skipping `.md` is a HARD FAILURE that has happened before — see batch 8 postmortem.**

```
knowledge/synapse/Wiki/{Schema}/{ObjectType}/{ObjectName}.lineage.md       ← PRODUCTION LINEAGE MAP (from Phase 10B Column Lineage) — written FIRST
knowledge/synapse/Wiki/{Schema}/{ObjectType}/{ObjectName}.md              ← THE WIKI DOC (full 8-section template, Elements table, 100+ lines)
knowledge/synapse/Wiki/{Schema}/{ObjectType}/{ObjectName}.review-needed.md ← REVIEW SIDECAR (Tier 4 items, reviewer corrections, questions — NOT the wiki)
knowledge/synapse/Wiki/{Schema}/{ObjectType}/{ObjectName}.alter.sql        ← ALTER SCRIPT (UC table comment + column comments + tags)
```

### File Identity Rules (DO NOT CONFUSE THESE)

| File | Contains | Does NOT contain |
|------|----------|------------------|
| **`.md`** | Full 8-section wiki template (Business Meaning, Business Logic, Query Advisory, Elements, Lineage, Relationships, Sample Queries, Atlassian). This is the PRIMARY artifact. | N/A — this is the complete document |
| **`.review-needed.md`** | Reviewer Corrections table, Tier 4 UNVERIFIED list, Clarification questions, Structural questions | The Elements table. Section headers like `## 1. Business Meaning`. Full column descriptions. If you see these, you're writing to the WRONG file. |
| **`.lineage.md`** | Column-level source mapping from Phase 10B | Wiki prose, element descriptions |
| **`.alter.sql`** | SET TBLPROPERTIES (table comment), SET TAGS, ALTER COLUMN COMMENT for EVERY column | Wiki prose. Must have one ALTER COLUMN per wiki element row. |

Object type folders: `Tables/`, `Views/`, `Functions/`

> Stored Procedures are not documentation targets. They are analyzed as inputs during table/view documentation (Phases 8, 9, 9B) but do not produce their own wiki files. Functions **are** documentation targets and produce wiki files in the `Functions/` folder.

All four files are mandatory outputs. The `.lineage.md` file captures the production-to-DWH column mapping from Phase 10B Column Lineage (SP code lineage analysis). The `.alter.sql` file is generated inline during Phase 11 — do NOT defer to Phase 11W.

> **Downstream propagation and deployment reports** are produced separately by Phase 11W (`11w-write-objects.mdc`) via the `write-objects-dwh` command. ALTER script GENERATION is part of Phase 11. ALTER script EXECUTION is part of Phase 11W.

### Write Order (MANDATORY)

1. **FIRST**: Confirm `{ObjectName}.lineage.md` exists (written by Phase 10B). If missing, Phase 11 cannot proceed.
2. **SECOND**: Write `{ObjectName}.md` — the wiki doc. Use the Write tool with the `.md` path. Verify the file contains all 8 `## N.` section headers.
3. **THIRD**: Write `{ObjectName}.review-needed.md` — the review sidecar. This is a SHORT file listing Tier 4 items and questions. It does NOT duplicate the wiki.
4. **FOURTH**: Write `{ObjectName}.alter.sql` — the ALTER script. Generate from the wiki Elements table. Every column row in the wiki MUST produce one ALTER COLUMN COMMENT statement per UC target table. Read `11w-write-objects.mdc` for the ALTER template (header, TBLPROPERTIES, TAGS, column comments). For dual UC targets (masked + PII), duplicate all ALTER COLUMN statements for both tables. **Exception**: If the object has no UC target (UC Target = `_Not_Migrated` or no generic pipeline mapping), skip the `.alter.sql` file entirely and note "No UC target" in the output check.

   **UC SQL comment text (HARD RULE)**: The wiki `.md` may use Unicode typography in tier tags (`—` em dash). Every string embedded in SQL (`COMMENT '...'`, `TBLPROPERTIES` text values) MUST be normalized with `knowledge/synapse/Wiki/_uc_comment_sanitize.py` (`sanitize_uc_sql_comment_text` or `escape_sql_comment_value`) so tier tags in SQL use ASCII: `(Tier N - source)`. This prevents CP1255 mojibake (e.g. `ג€"`) and broken tooling on Windows. Generators: `_batch_generate_lib.py`, `_deep_propagate_lib.py`, `_broadcast_propagate.py`, `tools/merge_wiki_column_comments_into_alter.py` already apply this — follow the same pattern for any new script.

   **⛔ ALTER TABLE target validation (HARD GATE)**: The fully-qualified name after `ALTER TABLE` MUST match `^[A-Za-z0-9_.]+$` — letters, digits, underscores, dots only. **NEVER paste the wiki UC Target prose cell into the SQL.** The wiki property table may contain human-readable text like "Not directly exported", "Gold/sql_dp_prod_we/...", "likely already in UC as ...", "(uc_table not assigned)" — that is for analysts. The ALTER script needs ONLY the resolved `main.{uc_table}` from live UC (`information_schema`) or `_generic_pipeline_mapping.json`. If resolution failed or produced no valid identifier, do NOT emit an ALTER TABLE with a fabricated or prose-like name — skip the `.alter.sql` entirely and note "UC resolution failed" in the output check. See `11w-write-objects.mdc` §4g for the full allowlist rules.

**ALTER TABLE object name (hard gate)** — The identifier after `ALTER TABLE` MUST be a real Unity Catalog path taken **only** from (a) verified `information_schema` / live UC resolution per `11w-write-objects.mdc` §4, or (b) `uc_table` in `knowledge/synapse/Wiki/_generic_pipeline_mapping.json`, emitted as `main.{uc_table}`. **Never** paste the wiki **UC Target** property cell, status sentences, datalake paths (`Gold/...`), or notes like `Not directly exported` into the SQL object position. If `uc_table` is empty and UC is unverified, **omit executable `ALTER TABLE` statements** (do not fabricate a name). Valid targets match `^[A-Za-z0-9_.]+$` with no spaces. See `11w-write-objects.mdc` §4g.

**⛔ ALTER COLUMN names = DDL columns only (HARD GATE — 2026-03-30)** — The text after `ALTER COLUMN` MUST be a **real column name** from Synapse/UC for this table (same names as the wiki Elements table / `INFORMATION_SCHEMA`). **NEVER** emit `ALTER COLUMN Tier 1`, `Tier 2`, … `Tier 5` — those are **documentation tier labels** that appear inside `(Tier N - source)` suffixes in COMMENT text, not physical columns. Emitting them causes Databricks `PARSE_SYNTAX_ERROR` (e.g. parser splits `Tier` and `4`). Spec: `.specify/specs/003-synapse-knowledge/spec.md` FR-012.

**⛔ Databricks backticks for special column names (HARD GATE — 2026-03-30)** — If a column name contains `/`, spaces, or reserved patterns, wrap it in **backticks**: `` ALTER COLUMN `Organic/Paid` COMMENT '...' ``. Synapse bracket notation does not apply in UC SQL. Spec: FR-013.

**⛔ File encoding (HARD RULE — 2026-03-30)**: ALL file writes (`.md`, `.review-needed.md`, `.lineage.md`, `.alter.sql`) MUST use explicit `encoding="utf-8"`. Never rely on system default encoding (Windows CP1252/CP1255 corrupts tier tags and special characters). Python: `open(path, "w", encoding="utf-8")` or Write tool (which is UTF-8 by default). This prevents mojibake at the source — the sanitizer (`_uc_comment_sanitize.py`) is a safety net, not a substitute for correct encoding.

**Self-check after each object**:
- Read back the `.md` file path and confirm it is non-empty and contains `## 4. Elements`. If the `.md` file is empty or missing, Phase 11 has FAILED for this object.
- Count element rows in the wiki (lines matching `| N |` in section 4). Count ALTER COLUMN statements in the `.alter.sql` file (per UC target). They MUST match. Emit: `ALTER COLUMN CHECK: wiki={N} alter={M} — PASS/FAIL`. If FAIL, fix the ALTER file before proceeding to the next object.
- **Name-level parity (HARD — 2026-03-30)**: For each ALTER COLUMN in `.alter.sql`, the column name (after stripping backticks and lowercasing) MUST match a wiki Element Name (column 2 of the Elements table, lowercased). Conversely, every wiki element MUST have a corresponding ALTER COLUMN. A **count match with name mismatch** (e.g. wiki has `ColumnA` but ALTER has `ColumnB`) is a HARD FAIL — the description would land on the wrong UC column. Emit: `ALTER NAME PARITY: {N} matched, {M} wiki-only, {K} alter-only — PASS/FAIL`. Run `python tools/audit_wiki_alter_comment_parity.py` on the file to validate both names and description text match.
- **UC ALTER target check**: Every `ALTER TABLE <x>` in `.alter.sql` must have `<x>` matching `^[A-Za-z0-9_.]+$` (no spaces). If FAIL, the generator pasted prose into the object name — replace `<x>` with `main.{uc_table}` from mapping or remove the alter. Run `python tools/audit_alter_uc_mapping.py` on the file when possible.
- Confirm all required files exist on disk: `.lineage.md`, `.md`, `.review-needed.md`, and `.alter.sql` (unless no UC target). A missing required file is a HARD FAIL.
- **Cross-object consistency check**: For every column that has lineage to a production source column, check if any existing wiki in `knowledge/synapse/Wiki/` already documents a column from that same source. If yes, verify the description matches verbatim. Emit: `CROSS-OBJECT CHECK: {N} shared columns checked, {M} mismatches — PASS/FAIL`. If FAIL, fix mismatched descriptions by copying from the canonical dimension wiki before proceeding.
- **ALTER TABLE target validation**: If `.alter.sql` was generated, read every `ALTER TABLE` line and verify the target name matches `^[A-Za-z0-9_.]+$`. If ANY target contains spaces, slashes, parentheses, or looks like English prose, the `.alter.sql` is INVALID — delete it and regenerate with proper UC resolution. Emit: `ALTER TARGET CHECK: {target_name} — PASS/FAIL`.
- **ALTER COLUMN sanity**: No line may match `ALTER COLUMN Tier` followed by a digit (bogus tier-as-column). No `ALTER COLUMN` for a name with `/` unless the name is backtick-wrapped. Run `python tools/audit_alter_uc_mapping.py` on the file. Emit: `ALTER COLUMN ID CHECK — PASS/FAIL`.

## STRICT RULES

1. **Use the query-brain template below** for ALL object types
2. **Copy the template EXACTLY** -- do not change section names, numbering, or order
3. **⛔ No table-level statistics in COLUMN descriptions — HARD ENFORCED** -- Column descriptions in the Elements table (Section 4) MUST NOT contain row counts, percentages, date ranges, or any snapshot-specific statistics. These numbers are stale tomorrow and waste context window for consumers. Examples of FORBIDDEN content in column descriptions:
   - `1=Standard (94%)` — the 94% is a snapshot stat. Write `1=Standard` instead
   - `698,747 rows (99.9%) have value=1` — row count, remove entirely
   - `132 test accounts (0.02%)` — row count + percentage, remove
   - `Top values: CySEC=7.39M, BVI=7.30M` — row counts per value, remove
   - `NULL for 107,646 users (15.4%)` — replace with `NULL when {semantic reason}`
   - `39,048 users (5.6%) are over their declared KYC limit (avg equity $46K vs avg limit $25.6K)` — move to Section 2 (Business Logic) if relevant, remove from column description
   
   **WHAT IS ALLOWED in column descriptions**: Dictionary value mappings (e.g., `0=Disabled, 1=Enabled`), FK references, computation formulas, NULL semantics (e.g., "NULL if not yet processed"), and business meaning. These are structural facts that don't change with time.
   
   **WHERE table stats belong**: Section 1 (Business Meaning) and Section 2 (Business Logic) may include row counts and distribution summaries at the TABLE level — these sections set context. Section 3 (Query Advisory) Gotchas may reference value distributions for analyst guidance. Column descriptions must be timeless.
   
   **When inheriting T1 descriptions from upstream wikis**: If the upstream wiki description contains percentages or row counts (e.g., `1=Standard (94%)`), strip the stats during inheritance. Copy the semantic content verbatim but remove snapshot-specific numbers. The upstream stats refer to the upstream table's distribution, which is doubly irrelevant in a downstream context
4. **DO include lookup value mappings** -- these define the system
5. **DO include query advisory** -- this is the core differentiator
6. **Every `{PLACEHOLDER}` must be replaced** with real content
7. **If a section does not apply**, write "N/A for {object type}." -- do NOT remove the section
8. **⛔ Elements table must list EVERY element — no skipping, no grouping, no delegation (HARD ENFORCED)** -- Every column the view/table exposes MUST have its own numbered row in the Elements table with a full description and tier suffix. The following shortcuts are FORBIDDEN and produce an invalid doc:
   - `2+ | All {Table} columns | a.* | See {Table}.md` -- this is a redirect, not documentation
   - `| All columns | See [Table.md](...) | (Tier 2 — inherited)` -- same problem, just linked
   - Any row that groups multiple columns into one line (e.g., "All Fact_X columns")
   - Any row with `*` or `a.*` as the source without expanding individual columns
   
   **Views are equal citizens.** A view that does `SELECT a.* FROM TableX a` has the SAME number of Element rows as `TableX`. If `TableX` has 130 columns, the view wiki has 130+ Element rows (plus any view-added columns like `DateKey`). For pass-through/untransformed columns, copy the description verbatim from the base table's wiki (same description, same tier, same source attribution). This is easy -- the base table wiki already exists, just read it and copy each row. For transformed columns or view-added columns (JOINs, CASE expressions, computed columns), write a new description with the appropriate tier. The view documentation exists because the VIEW is the object mapped to UC, queries hit the view, and the AI assistant needs every column described to help analysts.
9. **CODE IS KING** -- when sources conflict, the hierarchy from Constitution Section II is absolute: **Tier 5** (domain expert / glossary) > **Tier 1** (upstream wiki) > **Tier 2** (Synapse code from SSDT repo) > **Tier 2b** (DWH_Migration / BI_DB_Migration DDLs) > **Tier 3** (live data / sampling) > **Tier 3b** (DDL structure from SSDT repo) > **Tier 4-Atlassian** (Confluence/Jira — business meaning, not flagged `[UNVERIFIED]`) > **Tier 4-Inferred** (column name guessing — MUST flag `[UNVERIFIED]`). The upstream wiki has already gone through strict code-is-king analysis on production sources and is our authoritative starting point. Synapse code wins only for DWH-specific transformations and derived columns. DWH_Migration DDLs are authoritative for frozen dimensions unique to Synapse (e.g., Dim_AccountType). If Phase 2 sampling found 5 enum values but Confluence documents only 3, include all 5 and note the undocumented ones. Confluence provides business meaning and intent; upstream wiki and Synapse code/data provide truth.
10. **⛔ VERBATIM UPSTREAM INHERITANCE — HARD ENFORCED** -- when a column has no transformation (passthrough or rename) and an upstream wiki description exists, COPY-PASTE that description AS-IS into the Elements table. Do NOT rephrase, summarize, rewrite, or "improve" it. The ONLY modifications allowed: (a) strip snapshot-specific statistics like `(94%)` or `698K rows` — these are stale tomorrow, (b) optionally append "Passthrough from {relay table}." to note the DWH intermediate source. The upstream wiki's descriptions have already been validated through the full code-is-king pipeline. Your job is to be a photocopier, not an editor. If the upstream says "Score or decision from automated identity verification vendors (Onfido, Au10tix). NULL if not yet processed." — that is EXACTLY what you write. You do not drop vendor names. You do not drop NULL semantics. You do not change "match result" to "match status." See `10.5b-tier1-enforcement.mdc` Section 2b for the full enforcement protocol and the real failure example that triggered this rule.
11. **CONFIDENCE TIERS** -- every element description must be traceable to a source tier from the unified hierarchy in Constitution Section II. For the Elements table Confidence Tier Legend, tiers are grouped by star rating (sub-tiers share the same star count):

| Stars | Tiers | Tag | `[UNVERIFIED]`? |
|-------|-------|-----|-----------------|
| 5 stars | Tier 5 (domain expert / glossary) | `(Tier 5 — domain expert)` | No |
| 4 stars | Tier 1 (upstream wiki verbatim) | `(Tier 1 — upstream wiki, {source})` | No |
| 3 stars | Tier 2 (Synapse SP code) + Tier 2b (DWH_Migration / BI_DB_Migration DDLs) | `(Tier 2 — ...)` | No |
| 2 stars | Tier 3 (live data / sampling) + Tier 3b (DDL structure from SSDT repo) | `(Tier 3 — ...)` | No |
| 1.5 stars | Tier 4-Atlassian (Confluence/Jira business meaning) | `(Tier 4 — Confluence/Jira, {source})` | No |
| 1 star | Tier 4-Inferred (column name guessing) | `[UNVERIFIED] (Tier 4 — inferred)` | **Yes** |

Only Tier 4-Inferred descriptions carry the `[UNVERIFIED]` prefix. Tier 4-Atlassian descriptions are low-confidence but represent documented business intent. A Confidence Tier Legend table MUST be included in Section 4 before the Elements table. The full 8-tier hierarchy is in Rule 9 and Constitution Section II; this table shows how tiers map to star ratings.
12. **⛔ SHARED COLUMN = SAME DESCRIPTION (Cross-Object Consistency) — HARD ENFORCED** -- When a column in THIS object traces to the same production source as a column in an ALREADY-DOCUMENTED object (via `.lineage.md`), the description MUST be copied verbatim from the existing wiki. The canonical owner is the dimension/master table (e.g., `Dim_Position` owns position columns, `Dim_Customer` owns customer columns). All downstream tables (facts, BI_DB aggregates, snapshots) MUST inherit the dimension's description word-for-word — do NOT paraphrase, do NOT rewrite, do NOT change the tier. **Before writing any column description**: (a) read the `.lineage.md` file to identify the production source column, (b) search `knowledge/synapse/Wiki/` for any existing wiki that documents a column with the same production source, (c) if found, copy that description exactly including the tier suffix. Only APPEND a "DWH note:" prefix if this table applies a DWH-specific transformation the canonical table does not. If a column says "Same meaning as `Dim_X.Y`" in the lineage but has a DIFFERENT description, that is a HARD BUG — fix it before proceeding. Tier drift (e.g., Tier 1 in Dim but Tier 5 in Fact for the same source) is also a HARD BUG.
13. **REVIEW SIDECAR** -- alongside every wiki file, produce a `.review-needed.md` companion file listing all Tier 4 items and specific questions for domain experts. Path: same directory as the wiki file, named `{ObjectName}.review-needed.md`. This is not optional.
14. **FULL UPSTREAM SEARCH** -- before labeling any column as "DWH-specific" or writing a Tier 4 description, grep the entire upstream wiki folder (tables, views, related objects, all schemas) for the column name. Columns frequently originate from views, related tables, or history schemas — not just the source table. Only after an exhaustive search returns no results may a column be flagged as DWH-specific or given a Tier 4 description.
15. **REVIEWER CORRECTIONS (RERUN)** -- before generating, check if a `.review-needed.md` already exists for this object. If it contains a `## Reviewer Corrections` section with entries, read every row and apply them as **Tier 5** overrides. Tier 5 is absolute — it overrides all other tiers including upstream wiki (Tier 1). After applying, carry corrections forward in the new `.review-needed.md` with a `[RESOLVED]` marker so they persist across future reruns. **STALENESS CHECK**: For each Tier 5 override, compare the current Tier 1–3 description against the description that was current when the Tier 5 was written (recorded in the "Current (wrong)" column of the corrections table). If the Tier 1–3 description has materially changed (new computation, renamed column, different transformation logic, changed FK target — not just wording/formatting), the Tier 5 may be stale. In this case: (a) still apply the Tier 5 for now, but (b) add the column to a new `## Tier 5 Re-Review Needed` section in the sidecar, showing the original context, the Tier 5 correction, and the new Tier 1–3 description, so a domain expert can confirm or update. Tag the column `(Tier 5 — domain expert, RE-REVIEW)` in the wiki until confirmed.
16. **DOMAIN GLOSSARY** -- before generating, read `knowledge/glossary.md`. All acronym expansions, term definitions, and value maps in the glossary are Tier 5 authority. The pipeline MUST NOT infer alternative meanings for any term that has a glossary entry. Apply glossary terms wherever the term appears in element descriptions, business logic sections, or query advisory.
17. **TIER 5 IN ELEMENTS TABLE** -- when a description comes from reviewer corrections or the glossary, tag it `(Tier 5 — domain expert, {original source})` — preserving the original production source from the lineage file (e.g., `Trade.PositionTbl`, `ETL-computed`, `Trade.OpenPositionEndOfDay → join-enriched`). The Tier 5 label indicates the *description quality* was expert-confirmed; the source indicates *where the data comes from*. Both are required for traceability. Tier 5 entries are never flagged `[UNVERIFIED]` and never appear in the review sidecar's Tier 4 section.
18. **ALL 8 section headers MUST exist as separate `## N.` lines** -- collapsing sections (e.g., `## 2–8.`) is FORBIDDEN and produces an invalid doc. See "Inline Execution & Quality Enforcement" section below for full enforcement rules.
19. **Minimum line counts are mandatory** -- Tables: 100+ lines, Views: 80+ lines (but views wrapping large tables will be much larger — a view over a 130-column table needs 130+ Element rows alone). The 80-line minimum is a floor, not a target. See Rule B3 below. All documentation is generated inline by the parent agent — subagents are FORBIDDEN (see Rule B1).
20. **⛔ TIER SUFFIX ON EVERY COLUMN DESCRIPTION — HARD ENFORCED** -- Every element description in Section 4 MUST end with a tier suffix in the format `(Tier N — source.table)`. This is non-negotiable because Phase 11W (`write-objects-dwh`) extracts the Description field verbatim and writes it as the Unity Catalog column comment. The tier and source table are the provenance trail that travels with the column into UC — without them, consumers cannot assess description reliability. Examples:
    - `Primary key. Payment gateway endpoint identifier. (Tier 1 — Billing.Depot)`
    - `ETL load timestamp — set to GETDATE() on each reload. (Tier 2 — SP_Dictionaries_DL_To_Synapse)`
    - `[UNVERIFIED] Appears to be a risk score threshold. (Tier 4 — inferred)`
    - `Financial instrument display name. DWH note: truncated to varchar(50). (Tier 1 — Trade.Instrument)`
    - `Country name from IP2Location GeoIP database. (Tier 5 — domain expert, Dictionary.Country)`
    
    The suffix MUST include: (a) the tier number, (b) the tier label (upstream wiki / SP code / inferred / domain expert), and (c) the **ORIGIN source object** — the production table, SP, or upstream wiki that the description was ORIGINALLY derived from. **Tier tags are transitive**: if DWH_dbo.Dim_Position says `(Tier 1 — Trade.PositionTbl)` and BI_DB passes the column through, BI_DB says `(Tier 1 — Trade.PositionTbl)` — the relay is invisible. Only transformations earn an annotation; the origin never changes. See `GATE-lineage-contract.mdc` for the full transitivity rule. A separate Confidence column in the Elements table is permitted but does NOT substitute for the suffix in the description text. **Validation**: Phase 11's post-write gate (Rule B6, check 4) MUST verify every description ends with `(Tier`.
21. **⛔ COMPUTATION FORMULA ON TIER 2 COLUMNS — HARD ENFORCED** -- For every Tier 2 column derived from SP code, the description MUST include a **concise computation formula** showing HOW the sausage is made. This is the core value of a semantic layer — analysts need to know not just WHAT a metric means but HOW it is computed. The formula should be compact but complete enough that an analyst could reconstruct the query logic.

    **What to include by column type:**

    | Column Source Pattern | Formula Format |
    |-----------------------|----------------|
    | `SUM/COUNT/AVG(Amount)` with filters | `SUM(Amount) from Fact_CustomerAction WHERE ActionTypeID=N AND {filter}` |
    | CASE/IIF-derived flags | `CASE WHEN {condition} THEN 1 ELSE 0` or the actual branching logic |
    | Compensation subsets (ActionTypeID=36) | `ActionTypeID=36, CompensationReasonID IN (N,M,...)` — list the ACTUAL IDs |
    | Snapshot columns from FSE/V_Liabilities | `From {SourceView}.{ColumnName}` (already done for some — keep doing it) |
    | Hardcoded values / specific CID lists | Show the actual values: `CID IN (2244852, 2283663, ...)` |
    | Join-enriched lookups | `From {DimTable}.{Column} via {JoinColumn}` |
    | Day-over-day deltas | `today.{X} - yesterday.{X}` (name the source column) |
    | Function-computed | `Function_{Name}({params})` with a 1-line summary of the function's core logic |
    | Filtered aggregations by InstrumentType/Settlement | `WHERE IsSettled=1 AND InstrumentTypeID IN (5,6)` — list actual filter values |

    **Examples (GOOD vs BAD):**

    BAD: `"Compensation amounts classified as Performance Incentive (PI). Subset of compensation with PI-specific reason IDs."`
    GOOD: `"PI compensation. SUM(Amount) from Fact_CustomerAction WHERE ActionTypeID=36 AND CompensationReasonID IN (23,42,51). Performance Incentive payouts to popular investors."`

    BAD: `"Total deposits made by the customer on this date."`
    GOOD: `"Total deposits. SUM(Amount) from Fact_CustomerAction WHERE ActionTypeID=7, MoneyMovementReasonID NOT IN (internal transfer reasons). Excludes InternalTransferDeposits."`

    BAD: `"Net commission for real stock positions."`
    GOOD: `"Net commission for real stocks. SUM(Commission) from Fact_CustomerAction WHERE ActionTypeID IN (22,23) AND IsSettled=1 AND InstrumentTypeID IN (5,6). Client's commission share after eToro markup."`

    BAD: `"Day-over-day change in unrealized PnL for real crypto positions."`
    GOOD: `"Delta in unrealized PnL for real crypto. today.UnrealizedPnLCryptoReal - yesterday.UnrealizedPnLCryptoReal from Fact_CustomerUnrealized_PnL."`

    **Conciseness rule**: The formula should be SHORT — not a full SQL query. Use `SUM(Amount) WHERE ActionTypeID=36 AND ReasonID IN (...)` not a 10-line SELECT statement. The goal is an analyst reading this can immediately understand the filter criteria without reading the 9,500-line SP.

    **Phase 9 is the source**: The computation formulas come from Phase 9's column assignment extraction (Step 2/3/4). Phase 9 MUST capture the specific filter IDs, CASE branches, and aggregation expressions for each column. Phase 11 then embeds them in the description. If Phase 9 didn't capture the formula, go back and read the SP code for that column.

    **When formulas are unavailable**: If a column is a simple passthrough from a source view/table (e.g., `ClosingBalance FROM V_Liabilities.Liabilities`), the source reference is sufficient — no formula needed. Formulas are mandatory only for COMPUTED, AGGREGATED, or FILTERED columns.

    **⛔ FORBIDDEN VAGUE PHRASES — HARD BLACKLIST** (validated in Rule B6 check 7):

    If ANY Tier 2 element description contains one of these phrases, the description is **INVALID** and must be rewritten with actual values from the SP code:

    | Forbidden Phrase | Why It Fails | Fix |
    |------------------|-------------|-----|
    | "specific reason IDs" | Doesn't tell the analyst WHICH IDs | List the actual `CompensationReasonID IN (N,M,...)` |
    | "PI-specific reason IDs" | Same — which IDs? | `CompensationReasonID IN (23,42,51)` |
    | "affiliate-specific reason IDs" | Same | `CompensationReasonID IN (...)` |
    | "deposit-like in nature" | Vague business prose | List the actual filter: `MoneyMovementReasonID IN (...)` |
    | "with specific compensation reason IDs" | Vague | List them |
    | "specific fee type" / "fee types related to" | Which fee type? | `FeeTypeID IN (N,M)` or `ActionTypeID=35 AND FeeTypeID=N` |
    | "PI-specific" / "cashout-related" / "dividend fee type" | Adjective instead of filter | Replace with the actual WHERE clause values |
    | "certain conditions" / "specific conditions" | Meaningless | State the actual CASE WHEN condition |
    | "various" / "multiple" / "several" (when describing filter values) | Hides the actual values | List every value |
    | "excluded reasons are ... no longer applicable" | Why are they excluded? List them or drop the clause | Keep the exclusion list: `NOT IN (6,23,28,...)` — analysts need it |
    | "subset of" (without listing what subset) | Analyst can't reproduce the query | Follow with the actual WHERE filter |
    | "from specific money movement reasons" | Which reasons? | `MoneyMovementReasonID IN (...)` |

    **The test is simple**: Could an analyst reconstruct the SQL WHERE clause from the description alone? If not, the description is vague and must be rewritten.

    **When the SP is too large to find specific IDs**: If Phase 9 didn't capture the filter values for a column, Phase 11 MUST go back and read the relevant SP section. Use Grep to find the column name in the SP file, read the surrounding 50 lines, and extract the actual filter. Do NOT write a vague placeholder and move on.

